derived from Middle High German <i>esban</i>, <i>espan</i> ‘pasture’ (Bavarian and Swabian <i>Espan</i>).","North German and Danish: from a variant of the personal name <i>Jesper</i>, Danish and Low German form of   Kasper   and   Kaspar  , equivalents of   Casper  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Esber","meanings":["Arabic (Syria and Lebanon): from <i>Asbir</i>, of unknown meaning, used as a surname. Derivation from Arabic <i>aṣbar</i> ‘very patient’ is linguistically improbable (<i>ṣ</i> and <i>s</i> are not interchangeable). This surname is found among both Muslims and Christians. Compare   Esper   4 and   Asper   2.","Filipino: unexplained."]},{"name":"Kasper","meanings":["German, Danish, and Polish; Slovak (mainly <b>Kašper</b>); Czech and Slovenian (also <b>Kašper</b>): from the personal names <i>Kasper</i> (German, Danish, and Polish) and <i>Kašper</i> (Slovak, Czech, and Slovenian variant of <i>Gašpar</i>, <i>Kašpar</i>, and <i>Gašper</i>, respectively), equivalents of   Casper  . In North America, this surname is also a shortened and altered form of especially Polish patronymics and other derivatives, e.g.   Kasprzak  . See also   Kaspar  ,   Gaspar  , and   Gasper  ."]}]},{"name":"Hawise","type":"FIRST","meanings":["This female name (which has been corrupted down to Avice and Avis) is from Hadewisa, formed from the German name Hedvig, same as Edwig, which Wachter translates 'propugnator felicitatis;' say, 'fortunate soldier.'"],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705182,"age":1,"year":"1066","julianDay":2110409,"title":"Battle of Hastings","description":"Battle of Hastings was fought between the Norman-French army and the battle-wary English army on October 14, 1066. Duke William of Normandy believed he was the rightful king rather than Harold, who had been crowned king several months earlier. Harold was killed in battle and William was crowned king on Christmas Day 1066.","url":"https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/learn/1066-and-the-norman-conquest/what-happ